{"title_page": "Friday Afternoons", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n'''''Friday Afternoons''''' is a collection of s Ophir sophiacomposed 1933\u201335 for the pupils of Clive House School, [[Prestatyn]], where his brother, Robert, was headmaster.<ref>Oliver: p. 217</ref> Two of the songs, \"Cuckoo\" and \"Old Abram Brown\", were featured in the film ''[[Moonrise Kingdom]]''.\n\n== Composition ==\n\nNot long after graduating from the [[Royal College of Music]], Britten started composing his collection of mostly unison songs (the last song, \"Old Abram Brown\", being in [[Canon (music)|canon]]) to texts he selected from [[Walter de la Mare]]'s anthology ''Come Hither''.<ref>Palmer:  p. 273</ref> Britten noted in his diary on 2 November 1933 (just over a month before his twentieth birthday) that he had composed that afternoon \"a song, for R.H.M.B. & Clive House, very light & bad \u2013 'I mun be married a Sunday'\".<ref>Evans (2009): p. 152</ref> \"Ee-Oh!\" followed on 19 December.<ref>Evans (2009): pp. 157, 187</ref>\n\nThere was no further mention in Britten\u2019s diary of composing school songs until May 1934, when he spent time with Robert at Clive House and helped by coaching pupils in cricket and taking singing classes.<ref name=\"Evans09:210-11\">Evans (2009): pp. 210-11</ref> He then resumed work on his songs, including \"A New Year Carol\", a setting of the traditional \"[[Levy-Dew]]\".<ref name= \"Evans09:210-11\"/> He completed the collection in August 1935 with the song \"Begone, Dull Care\".<ref>Britten (1991): p. 375</ref>\n\nThe title of the collection was originally ''Twelve Songs for Schools'',<ref>Evans (2009): p. 285</ref> but at the suggestion of Robert Britten was changed to ''Friday Afternoons'', since class singing was held at Clive House at that time in the week.<ref name=Bridcut127/> Britten dedicated ''Friday Afternoons'' \"To R.H.M. Britten and the boys of Clive House, Prestatyn\".<ref name=Bridcut127>Bridcut (2006): p. 127</ref>\n\n== Songs ==\n\n# \"Begone, Dull Care\" (Anon.)\n# \"A Tragic Story\" ([[Thackeray]])\n# \"Cuckoo!\" ([[Jane Taylor (poet)|Jane Taylor]])\n# \"Ee-Oh!\" (Anon.)\n# \"[[Levy-Dew|A New Year Carol]]\" (Anon., ed. [[Walter de la Mare]])\n# \"I Mun Be Married on Sunday\" ([[Nicholas Udall]])\n# \"There Was a Man of Newington\" (Anon.)\n# \"Fishing Song\" ([[Izaak Walton]])\n# \"The Useful Plough\" (Anon.)\n# \"Jazz-Man\" ([[Eleanor Farjeon]])\n# \"There Was a Monkey\" (Anon.)\n# \"Old Abram Brown\" (Anon.)\n\n== Critical reception ==\nThe classical music writer [[Michael Oliver (writer, broadcaster)|Michael Oliver]] has said that ''Friday Afternoons'' exemplifies Britten's ability to write melodies of the kind which \"insists on being sung and, once sung, lodges in the memory.\" <ref>Oliver, p. 51</ref> [[John Bridcut]] has pointed out that Britten's use of canon in \"Old Abram Brown\" \u2013 a \"little ''coup de ma\u00eetre'' [which] makes the funeral march great fun to sing\"<ref>Bridcut (2006): p. 23</ref> \u2014 was a technique he was to reuse in several future works such as ''[[A Ceremony of Carols]]'' (\"This Little Babe\") and ''[[Noye's Fludde]]''. When the first recording was made of almost the entire collection (omitting \"Ee-oh\") by the Choir of Downside School, Purley on [[Decca Records|Decca]], reviewer Diana McVeagh in ''[[The Musical Times]]'' described some of the songs having \"a spell-binding enchantment \u2014 ''A New Year Carol'' is as healing as 'Jack shall have Jill' in ''[[A Midsummer Night's Dream (opera)|The Dream]]''.\"<ref>{{cite journal | last =McVeagh | first =Diana | authorlink = | title =Review: Gemini Variations; Psalm 150; Songs from Friday Afternoons by Britten, Gabriel Jeney, ZoltanJeney, Viola Tunnard, Choir of Downside School and Purley | journal =The Musical Times | volume = 108 | issue =1494  | pages =714\u2013715 | publisher =Musical Times Publications Ltd | location = | date =August 1967 | language = | jstor =952257 | issn = | doi = 10.2307/952257| id = | mr = | zbl = | jfm = }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist|2}}\n'''Cited sources'''\n\n* {{cite book | last = Bridcut | first = John | year = 2006 | title = Britten's Children | location = London | publisher = Faber and Faber | isbn = 0571228399}}\n* {{cite book | last = Britten | first = Benjamin |editor=Donald Mitchell | year = 1991 | title = Letters From a Life: The Selected Letters of Benjamin Britten, Volume I, 1923\u20131939 | location = London | publisher = Faber and Faber | isbn = 057115221X }}\n* {{cite book | last = Evans | first = John | year = 2009 | title = Journeying Boy: The Diaries of the Young Benjamin Britten 1928\u20131938 | location = London | publisher = Faber and Faber | isbn = 0571238831}}\n* {{cite book | last = Oliver | first = Michael | year = 1996 | title = Benjamin Britten | location = London | publisher = Phaidon Press | isbn = 0714832774}}\n* {{cite book | last = Palmer | first = ed. Christopher | year = 1984 | title = The Britten Companion | location = London | publisher = Faber and Faber | isbn = 0571131476}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.fridayafternoonsmusic.co.uk/ Friday Afternoons project], providing free downloads of lyrics, scores and teaching resources\n\n{{Benjamin Britten|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Compositions by Benjamin Britten]]\n[[Category:Choral compositions]]\n[[Category:Children's songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n'''''Friday Afternoons''''' is a collection of 12 songs by [[Benjamin Britten]], composed 1933\u201335 for the pupils of Clive House School, [[Prestatyn]], where his brother, Robert, was headmaster.<ref>Oliver: p. 217</ref> Two of the songs, \"Cuckoo\" and \"Old Abram Brown\", were featured in the film ''[[Moonrise Kingdom]]''.\n\n== Composition ==\n\nNot long after graduating from the [[Royal College of Music]], Britten started composing his collection of mostly unison songs (the last song, \"Old Abram Brown\", being in [[Canon (music)|canon]]) to texts he selected from [[Walter de la Mare]]'s anthology ''Come Hither''.<ref>Palmer:  p. 273</ref> Britten noted in his diary on 2 November 1933 (just over a month before his twentieth birthday) that he had composed that afternoon \"a song, for R.H.M.B. & Clive House, very light & bad \u2013 'I mun be married a Sunday'\".<ref>Evans (2009): p. 152</ref> \"Ee-Oh!\" followed on 19 December.<ref>Evans (2009): pp. 157, 187</ref>\n\nThere was no further mention in Britten\u2019s diary of composing school songs until May 1934, when he spent time with Robert at Clive House and helped by coaching pupils in cricket and taking singing classes.<ref name=\"Evans09:210-11\">Evans (2009): pp. 210-11</ref> He then resumed work on his songs, including \"A New Year Carol\", a setting of the traditional \"[[Levy-Dew]]\".<ref name= \"Evans09:210-11\"/> He completed the collection in August 1935 with the song \"Begone, Dull Care\".<ref>Britten (1991): p. 375</ref>\n\nThe title of the collection was originally ''Twelve Songs for Schools'',<ref>Evans (2009): p. 285</ref> but at the suggestion of Robert Britten was changed to ''Friday Afternoons'', since class singing was held at Clive House at that time in the week.<ref name=Bridcut127/> Britten dedicated ''Friday Afternoons'' \"To R.H.M. Britten and the boys of Clive House, Prestatyn\".<ref name=Bridcut127>Bridcut (2006): p. 127</ref>\n\n== Songs ==\n\n# \"Begone, Dull Care\" (Anon.)\n# \"A Tragic Story\" ([[Thackeray]])\n# \"Cuckoo!\" ([[Jane Taylor (poet)|Jane Taylor]])\n# \"Ee-Oh!\" (Anon.)\n# \"[[Levy-Dew|A New Year Carol]]\" (Anon., ed. [[Walter de la Mare]])\n# \"I Mun Be Married on Sunday\" ([[Nicholas Udall]])\n# \"There Was a Man of Newington\" (Anon.)\n# \"Fishing Song\" ([[Izaak Walton]])\n# \"The Useful Plough\" (Anon.)\n# \"Jazz-Man\" ([[Eleanor Farjeon]])\n# \"There Was a Monkey\" (Anon.)\n# \"Old Abram Brown\" (Anon.)\n\n== Critical reception ==\nThe classical music writer [[Michael Oliver (writer, broadcaster)|Michael Oliver]] has said that ''Friday Afternoons'' exemplifies Britten's ability to write melodies of the kind which \"insists on being sung and, once sung, lodges in the memory.\" <ref>Oliver, p. 51</ref> [[John Bridcut]] has pointed out that Britten's use of canon in \"Old Abram Brown\" \u2013 a \"little ''coup de ma\u00eetre'' [which] makes the funeral march great fun to sing\"<ref>Bridcut (2006): p. 23</ref> \u2014 was a technique he was to reuse in several future works such as ''[[A Ceremony of Carols]]'' (\"This Little Babe\") and ''[[Noye's Fludde]]''. When the first recording was made of almost the entire collection (omitting \"Ee-oh\") by the Choir of Downside School, Purley on [[Decca Records|Decca]], reviewer Diana McVeagh in ''[[The Musical Times]]'' described some of the songs having \"a spell-binding enchantment \u2014 ''A New Year Carol'' is as healing as 'Jack shall have Jill' in ''[[A Midsummer Night's Dream (opera)|The Dream]]''.\"<ref>{{cite journal | last =McVeagh | first =Diana | authorlink = | title =Review: Gemini Variations; Psalm 150; Songs from Friday Afternoons by Britten, Gabriel Jeney, ZoltanJeney, Viola Tunnard, Choir of Downside School and Purley | journal =The Musical Times | volume = 108 | issue =1494  | pages =714\u2013715 | publisher =Musical Times Publications Ltd | location = | date =August 1967 | language = | jstor =952257 | issn = | doi = 10.2307/952257| id = | mr = | zbl = | jfm = }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist|2}}\n'''Cited sources'''\n\n* {{cite book | last = Bridcut | first = John | year = 2006 | title = Britten's Children | location = London | publisher = Faber and Faber | isbn = 0571228399}}\n* {{cite book | last = Britten | first = Benjamin |editor=Donald Mitchell | year = 1991 | title = Letters From a Life: The Selected Letters of Benjamin Britten, Volume I, 1923\u20131939 | location = London | publisher = Faber and Faber | isbn = 057115221X }}\n* {{cite book | last = Evans | first = John | year = 2009 | title = Journeying Boy: The Diaries of the Young Benjamin Britten 1928\u20131938 | location = London | publisher = Faber and Faber | isbn = 0571238831}}\n* {{cite book | last = Oliver | first = Michael | year = 1996 | title = Benjamin Britten | location = London | publisher = Phaidon Press | isbn = 0714832774}}\n* {{cite book | last = Palmer | first = ed. Christopher | year = 1984 | title = The Britten Companion | location = London | publisher = Faber and Faber | isbn = 0571131476}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.fridayafternoonsmusic.co.uk/ Friday Afternoons project], providing free downloads of lyrics, scores and teaching resources\n\n{{Benjamin Britten|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Compositions by Benjamin Britten]]\n[[Category:Choral compositions]]\n[[Category:Children's songs]]\n", "name_user": "91.73.156.34", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Good)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Friday_Afternoons"}
{"title_page": "Kaloor", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Kaloor\n| native_name             = \u0d15\u0d32\u0d42\u0d30\u0d4d\u200d\n| native_name_lang        = ml\n| other_name              = \n| nickname                = \n| settlement_type         = Neighbourhood\n| image_skyline           = Kaloor Junction.png\n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = '''Kaloor Junction'''\n| pushpin_map             = India Kerala\n| pushpin_label_position  = right\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in Kerala, India\n| coordinates             = {{coord|9.994|N|76.292|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Kerala]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Ernakulam district|Ernakulam]]\n| established_title       = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| named_for               = \n| government_type         = \n| governing_body          = \n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_total_km2          = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_total        = \n| population_as_of        = \n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| demographics_type1      = Languages\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]], [[English language|English]]\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code             = 682017<ref>http://pincode.cc/KERALA/ERNAKULAM/KALOOR/index.html</ref>\n| registration_plate      = KL-07\n| blank1_name_sec1        = [[Lok Sabha]] constituency\n| blank1_info_sec1        = Ernakulam\n| blank2_name_sec1        = Civic agency\n| blank2_info_sec1        = [[Kochi Municipal Corporation]]\n| blank1_name_sec2        = Avg. summer temperature\n| blank1_info_sec2        = {{convert|35|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}}\n| blank2_name_sec2        = Avg. winter temperature\n| blank2_info_sec2        = {{convert|20|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}}\n| website                 = http://kaloor.info\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\n'''Kaloor''' is a downtown [[:Category:Regions of Kochi|region]] in the [[Kochi|city of Kochi]], in the [[Kerala|state of Kerala]], [[India]]. It is just 2&nbsp;km from the [[Ernakulam Town railway station|Ernakulam North Railway Station]]. Kaloor Junction is also the name of a major intersection in this part of the city, intersecting the two major arteries of downtown Kochi, namely [[Banerji Road]] and the [[Kaloor-Kadavanthra Road]]. The nearest major intersections are [[Palarivattom]] to the east and Lissie Junction to the west.\n\nKaloor is especially notable for being home to the second largest stadium in the state after [[Trivandrum International Stadium]], the [[Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium, Kochi|Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium]]. The stadium plays host to cricket and football tournaments and is one of the venues of the [[FIFA World Cup|U-17 FIFA World Cup]] to be held in October 2017. Kaloor is also home to the Regional Centre of the [[Indira Gandhi National Open University|Indira Gandhi National Open University (IGNOU)]].<ref name=\"Welcome to IGNOU Cochin Regional Centre\">{{Cite web |url=http://rccochin.ignou.ac.in/ |title=Welcome to IGNOU Cochin Regional Centre |date=2019-07-25 |website=rccochin.ignou.ac.in |access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref> The suburb leads directly to the temple town suburb of Elamakkara and is the birthplace of noted Malayalam poet [[Vyloppilli_Sreedhara_Menon|Vylopillil Sreedhara Menon]]. It is well connected to all suburbs in Kochi and outlying areas and has its own bus terminus. The nearest railway station is [[Ernakulam Town|Ernakulam North Station.]] The Ernakulam South Junction Railway Station and the state run KSRTC bus stand are also at reachable distance. The [[Kochi Metro]] has a [[Kaloor metro station|station]] located at Kaloor Junction, making it easily accessible from both Aluva and Tripunithura sides of the city.\n\n[[Mathrubhumi]] and [[Deshabhimani]], two of Kerala's biggest media houses also have their head office around the vicinity of Kaloor.<ref name=\"Mathrubhumi Milestones\">{{Cite web |url=https://media.mathrubhumi.com/static/Milestones.html |title=Mathrubhumi Milestones |date=2019-07-25 |website=media.mathrubhumi.com |access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref><ref name=\"Deshabhimani\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.deshabhimani.com/about-us |title=Deshabhimani |date=2019-07-25 |website=Deshabhimani |language=en |access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref> The famous shrine of St. Antony is also situated in Kaloor. It holds its weekly novenas on every Tuesday, for which devotees of all faiths come from far and wide. The Kaloor market is also among the biggest in Kochi and is famous for the fresh produce and variety of meat and vegetables that are stocked by its merchants.\n\nIn recent years, Kaloor has become a favorite hangout joint of youngsters, with the opening of numerous boutique cafes, hip ice cream parlors and specialty restaurants.\n\nThe Kochi International Airport is situated 25&nbsp;km from Kaloor. Kochi International Seaport and Cochin shipyard are located around 14&nbsp;km from Kaloor.\n\n==Educational Institutions near by==\n*Indira Gandhi National Open University - Regional Centre\n\n==Main places==\n* [[Mathrubhumi]] <ref>http://www.mathrubhumi.com/</ref>\n* PVS Memorial Hospital<ref>http://www.pvsmemorialhospital.com/</ref>\n* [[New Indian Express]] Building\n* [[Seventh-day Adventist Higher Secondary School, Kochi]]\n* Kaloor Private Bus Stand\n* Kaloor Metro Station\n* [[Indira Gandhi National Open University]] - Regional Centre\n* [[Cochin Stock Exchange]]<ref name=\"Cochin Stock Exchange\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cochinstockexchange.com/ |title=Cochin Stock Exchange |date=2019-07-25 |website=www.cochinstockexchange.com |access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref>\n* [[Life Insurance Corporation of India|LIC]]\n* [[Gokulam Gopalan|Sree Gokulam Convention Centre]]\n* Central Administrative Tribunal<ref>http://cgat.gov.in/bench.htm</ref>\n* Accountant General Staff Quarters\n* Kaloor Market\n* [http://www.tulsidevelopers.org/tulsi-v-home-apartments.html Tulsi Developers]\n* [http://www.minimuthoottu.com/ Mini Muthoottu Tech Towers, Opp. Gokulam Park Hotel, Kaloor.]\n* [[Model Technical Higher Secondary School, Kaloor]]\n* [[Reserve Bank of India|Reserve Bank Of India]] - Sub Office\n* ACS Higher Secondary English Medium School, ACS School Road, Kaloor\n* Cherathrikovil Temple Auditorium, Azad Road\n* Pavakulam Temple\n*Chammany Tower, kaloor Junction\n* [https://vofoxsolutions.com/ Offshore Software Development Company In India - Vofox Solutions Pvt Ltd]\n<ref>[https://www.reviewsxp.com/blog/best-software-development-companies/ Software Development Company In India].Reviewsxp.com. Retrieved on 20 March 2020</ref>\n\n==Temples==\n* [http://www.cherathrikovil.com Cherathrikovil Sree Krishna - Mahadeva Temple, Azad Road, Kaloor]\n* Sri Pavakulam Temple, Kaloor - Elamakkara Road <ref>http://www.pavakkulam.com</ref>\n* Cheratrikovil Sri Krishna- Mahadeva Temple, Azad Road\n* Araamcheri Bhagavathy Temple, Ashram Lane, Azad Road\n* Amruthanandamayi Ashram, Ashram Lane, Azad Road\n* [[Sree Narayana Dharma Paripalana]] Seva Sangam Sree Narayana Guru Deva Temple, Azad Road\n* Pattupurakkal Bhagavathi Temple, Ashoka Road\n* Anandha Chandrodayam Sri Subhramanya Temple, ACS Road\n\n==Churches==\n* St. Antony's Shrine, Kaloor<ref>http://www.st-antonykaloor.org/index.html</ref>\n* St. Francis Xavier's Church, Kathrikadavu-Kaloor\n* Little Flower Church, Pottakuzhy-Kaloor\n* St. Jude's Church, Thamannam - Kathrikadavu Road\n* St. George Church, Perandoor\n* St. Antony's Church, Thannikkal\n\n==Mosques==\n* Kaloor Muslim Jama'at, Karukapilly, Kaloor\n* Da'wa Masjid, Kattayil Road, Pottakkuzhi\n* Thottathumpadi Muslim Jamaath Juma Masjid (Highway Masjid), Manappattipparambu Jn.\n* Salafi Masjid, Karukappilly\n* Taqwa Juma Masjid, Elamakkara Road\n* Juma Masjid, Puthukkalavattom Rd, Elamakkara\n\n==Location==\n{{Geographic Location\n|title     = '''Areas of Kochi'''\n|Northwest = [[Pachalam]]\n|North     = [[Perandoor]]\n|Northeast = [[Elamakkara]]\n|West      = [[Ernakulam]], [[Thoppumpady]] and [[Mundamveli]]\n|Centre    = Kaloor\n|East      = [[Palarivattom]]\n|Southwest = [[Mar Augustine Memorial Lisie Hospital|Lissie Hospital]]\n|South     = [[Kathrikadavu]]\n|Southeast = [[Thammanam]]\n}}\n\n==Suburbs of Kaloor==\n\n'''On LFC Road (Perandoor Road)'''\n* Pottakkuzhi and Elamakkara\n* Pavakkulam Temple, Da'wa Masjid and Little Flower Church\n* South Indian Bank and Nehan Tourism\n\n'''On Edappally Road'''\n* Deshabimani Jn, Palarivattom, Mamangalam, Edappally and Lulu Mall\n* Kalamassery, Aluva, Nedumbassery (Cochin Airport) and Angamaly\n\n'''On High Court Road'''\n* North Railway Station, Kacherippadi, MG Road, Albert's College and High Court\n* Marine Drive, Menaka and Boat Jetty\n* Law College, Cochin Corporation Office, General Hospital and Maharajas College\n\n'''On Kadavanthra Road'''\n* Kathrukadavu, Vinayaka and Kadavanthra\n* KP Vallon Road and Panampally Nagar\n* South Railway Station and Vyttila\n\n==Gallery==\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Kaloor.jpg|Jawaharlal Nehru International Stadium, Kaloor\nFile:Kaloor Bus Station.JPG|Kaloor Bus Station\nFile:JNU-Stadium-kaloor-cochin.jpg|Jawaharlal Nehru International Stadium, Kaloor\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{commons category}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Neighbourhoods of Kochi}}\n\n[[Category:Regions of Kochi]]\n[[Category:Neighbourhoods in Kochi]]\n\n\n{{ernakulam-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Kaloor\n| native_name             = \u0d15\u0d32\u0d42\u0d30\u0d4d\u200d\n| native_name_lang        = ml\n| other_name              = \n| nickname                = \n| settlement_type         = Neighbourhood\n| image_skyline           = Kaloor Junction.png\n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = '''Kaloor Junction'''\n| pushpin_map             = India Kerala\n| pushpin_label_position  = right\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in Kerala, India\n| coordinates             = {{coord|9.994|N|76.292|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Kerala]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Ernakulam district|Ernakulam]]\n| established_title       = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| named_for               = \n| government_type         = \n| governing_body          = \n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_total_km2          = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_total        = \n| population_as_of        = \n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| demographics_type1      = Languages\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]], [[English language|English]]\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = [[Postal Index Number