f noted Malayalam poet [[Vyloppilli_Sreedhara_Menon|Vylopillil Sreedhara Menon]]. It is well connected to all suburbs in Kochi and outlying areas and has its own bus terminus. The nearest railway station is [[Ernakulam Town|Ernakulam North Station.]] The Ernakulam South Junction Railway Station and the state run KSRTC bus stand are also at reachable distance. The [[Kochi Metro]] has a [[Kaloor metro station|station]] located at Kaloor Junction, making it easily accessible from both Aluva and Tripunithura sides of the city.\n\n[[Mathrubhumi]] and [[Deshabhimani]], two of Kerala's biggest media houses also have their head office around the vicinity of Kaloor.<ref name=\"Mathrubhumi Milestones\">{{Cite web |url=https://media.mathrubhumi.com/static/Milestones.html |title=Mathrubhumi Milestones |date=2019-07-25 |website=media.mathrubhumi.com |access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref><ref name=\"Deshabhimani\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.deshabhimani.com/about-us |title=Deshabhimani |date=2019-07-25 |website=Deshabhimani |language=en |access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref> The famous shrine of St. Antony is also situated in Kaloor. It holds its weekly novenas on every Tuesday, for which devotees of all faiths come from far and wide. The Kaloor market is also among the biggest in Kochi and is famous for the fresh produce and variety of meat and vegetables that are stocked by its merchants.\n\nIn recent years, Kaloor has become a favorite hangout joint of youngsters, with the opening of numerous boutique cafes, hip ice cream parlors and specialty restaurants.\n\nThe Kochi International Airport is situated 25&nbsp;km from Kaloor. Kochi International Seaport and Cochin shipyard are located around 14&nbsp;km from Kaloor.\n\n==Educational Institutions near by==\n*Indira Gandhi National Open University - Regional Centre\n\n==Main places==\n* [[Mathrubhumi]] <ref>http://www.mathrubhumi.com/</ref>\n* PVS Memorial Hospital<ref>http://www.pvsmemorialhospital.com/</ref>\n* [[New Indian Express]] Building\n* [[Seventh-day Adventist Higher Secondary School, Kochi]]\n* Kaloor Private Bus Stand\n* Kaloor Metro Station\n* [[Indira Gandhi National Open University]] - Regional Centre\n* [[Cochin Stock Exchange]]<ref name=\"Cochin Stock Exchange\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cochinstockexchange.com/ |title=Cochin Stock Exchange |date=2019-07-25 |website=www.cochinstockexchange.com |access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref>\n* [[Life Insurance Corporation of India|LIC]]\n* [[Gokulam Gopalan|Sree Gokulam Convention Centre]]\n* Central Administrative Tribunal<ref>http://cgat.gov.in/bench.htm</ref>\n* Accountant General Staff Quarters\n* Kaloor Market\n* [http://www.tulsidevelopers.org/tulsi-v-home-apartments.html Tulsi Developers]\n* [http://www.minimuthoottu.com/ Mini Muthoottu Tech Towers, Opp. Gokulam Park Hotel, Kaloor.]\n* [[Model Technical Higher Secondary School, Kaloor]]\n* [[Reserve Bank of India|Reserve Bank Of India]] - Sub Office\n* ACS Higher Secondary English Medium School, ACS School Road, Kaloor\n* Cherathrikovil Temple Auditorium, Azad Road\n* Pavakulam Temple\n*Chammany Tower, kaloor Junction\n* [https://vofoxsolutions.com/software-development-company-india/ Software Development Company In India - Vofox Solutions Pvt Ltd]\n<ref>[https://www.reviewsxp.com/blog/best-software-development-companies/ Software Development Company In India].Reviewsxp.com. Retrieved on 20 March 2020</ref>\n\n==Temples==\n* [http://www.cherathrikovil.com Cherathrikovil Sree Krishna - Mahadeva Temple, Azad Road, Kaloor]\n* Sri Pavakulam Temple, Kaloor - Elamakkara Road <ref>http://www.pavakkulam.com</ref>\n* Cheratrikovil Sri Krishna- Mahadeva Temple, Azad Road\n* Araamcheri Bhagavathy Temple, Ashram Lane, Azad Road\n* Amruthanandamayi Ashram, Ashram Lane, Azad Road\n* [[Sree Narayana Dharma Paripalana]] Seva Sangam Sree Narayana Guru Deva Temple, Azad Road\n* Pattupurakkal Bhagavathi Temple, Ashoka Road\n* Anandha Chandrodayam Sri Subhramanya Temple, ACS Road\n\n==Churches==\n* St. Antony's Shrine, Kaloor<ref>http://www.st-antonykaloor.org/index.html</ref>\n* St. Francis Xavier's Church, Kathrikadavu-Kaloor\n* Little Flower Church, Pottakuzhy-Kaloor\n* St. Jude's Church, Thamannam - Kathrikadavu Road\n* St. George Church, Perandoor\n* St. Antony's Church, Thannikkal\n\n==Mosques==\n* Kaloor Muslim Jama'at, Karukapilly, Kaloor\n* Da'wa Masjid, Kattayil Road, Pottakkuzhi\n* Thottathumpadi Muslim Jamaath Juma Masjid (Highway Masjid), Manappattipparambu Jn.\n* Salafi Masjid, Karukappilly\n* Taqwa Juma Masjid, Elamakkara Road\n* Juma Masjid, Puthukkalavattom Rd, Elamakkara\n\n==Location==\n{{Geographic Location\n|title     = '''Areas of Kochi'''\n|Northwest = [[Pachalam]]\n|North     = [[Perandoor]]\n|Northeast = [[Elamakkara]]\n|West      = [[Ernakulam]], [[Thoppumpady]] and [[Mundamveli]]\n|Centre    = Kaloor\n|East      = [[Palarivattom]]\n|Southwest = [[Mar Augustine Memorial Lisie Hospital|Lissie Hospital]]\n|South     = [[Kathrikadavu]]\n|Southeast = [[Thammanam]]\n}}\n\n==Suburbs of Kaloor==\n\n'''On LFC Road (Perandoor Road)'''\n* Pottakkuzhi and Elamakkara\n* Pavakkulam Temple, Da'wa Masjid and Little Flower Church\n* South Indian Bank and Nehan Tourism\n\n'''On Edappally Road'''\n* Deshabimani Jn, Palarivattom, Mamangalam, Edappally and Lulu Mall\n* Kalamassery, Aluva, Nedumbassery (Cochin Airport) and Angamaly\n\n'''On High Court Road'''\n* North Railway Station, Kacherippadi, MG Road, Albert's College and High Court\n* Marine Drive, Menaka and Boat Jetty\n* Law College, Cochin Corporation Office, General Hospital and Maharajas College\n\n'''On Kadavanthra Road'''\n* Kathrukadavu, Vinayaka and Kadavanthra\n* KP Vallon Road and Panampally Nagar\n* South Railway Station and Vyttila\n\n==Gallery==\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Kaloor.jpg|Jawaharlal Nehru International Stadium, Kaloor\nFile:Kaloor Bus Station.JPG|Kaloor Bus Station\nFile:JNU-Stadium-kaloor-cochin.jpg|Jawaharlal Nehru International Stadium, Kaloor\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{commons category}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Neighbourhoods of Kochi}}\n\n[[Category:Regions of Kochi]]\n[[Category:Neighbourhoods in Kochi]]\n\n\n{{ernakulam-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jomy19", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMain places", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kaloor"}
{"title_page": "...To Save Us All from Satan's Power", "text_new": "{{unref|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox television episode\n| title = ...To Save Us All from Satan's Power\n| series = [[The Sopranos]]\n| season = 3\n| episode = 10\n| guests= ''see below''\n| airdate = April 29, 2001\n| length = 45 minutes\n| production = 310\n| writer = [[Robin Green]]<br />[[Mitchell Burgess]]\n| director = [[Jack Bender]]\n| photographer = [[Alik Sakharov]]\n| episode_list = List of The Sopranos episodes\n| season_article = The Sopranos (season 3)\n| image = Sopranos ep310.jpg\n| image_size = 300px\n| prev = [[The Telltale Moozadell]]\n| next = [[Pine Barrens (The Sopranos)|Pine Barrens]]\n}}\n\n\"'''...To Save Us All from Satan's Power'''\" is the 36th episode of the [[HBO]] original series ''[[The Sopranos]]'' and the 10th of the show's third season. It was written by [[Robin Green]] and [[Mitchell Burgess]], and directed by [[Jack Bender]], and originally aired on April 29, 2001.\n\n==Starring==\n* [[James Gandolfini]] as [[Tony Soprano]]\n* [[Lorraine Bracco]] as [[Dr. Jennifer Melfi]]\n* [[Edie Falco]] as [[Carmela Soprano]]\n* [[Michael Imperioli]] as [[Christopher Moltisanti]]\n* [[Dominic Chianese]] as [[Junior Soprano|Corrado Soprano, Jr.]]\n* [[Steven Van Zandt]] as [[Silvio Dante]]\n* [[Tony Sirico]] as [[Paulie Gualtieri]]\n* [[Jamie-Lynn Sigler]] as [[Meadow Soprano]]\n* [[Robert Iler]] as [[Anthony Soprano, Jr.]]\n* [[Drea de Matteo]] as [[Adriana La Cerva]] *\n* [[Aida Turturro]] as [[Janice Soprano]]\n* [[John Ventimiglia]] as [[Artie Bucco]]\n* [[Kathrine Narducci]] as [[Charmaine Bucco]]\n* [[Steven R. Schirripa]] as [[Bobby Baccalieri]]\n* [[Federico Castelluccio]] as [[Furio Giunta]]\n* [[Robert Funaro]] as [[Eugene Pontecorvo]]\n\n''* = credit only''\n\n===Guest starring===\n* [[Jerry Adler]] as [[Hesh Rabkin]]\n\n====Also guest starring====\n* [[Vitali Baganov]] as [[List of characters from The Sopranos in the Soprano crime family#Valery|Valery]]\n* [[Joseph Badalucco Jr.|Joe Badulucco]] as [[Jimmy Altieri]] (''[[Flashback (narrative)|flashback]] sequences'')\n* [[Jason Cerbone]] as [[Jackie Aprile, Jr.]]\n* Matthew Cerbone as  Young [[Jackie Aprile, Jr.]] (''flashback sequences'')\n* Andrew Davoli as [[List of characters from The Sopranos in the Soprano crime family#Dino Zerilli|Dino Zerilli]]\n* John Fiore as [[List of characters from The Sopranos in the Soprano crime family#Gigi Cestone|Gigi Cestone]] (''flashback sequences'')\n* [[Dan Grimaldi]] as [[Patsy Parisi]]\n* George Loros as [[Ray Curto]]\n* [[Vincent Pastore]] as [[Big Pussy Bonpensiero]] (''flashback sequences'')\n* [[Turk Pipkin]] as [[List of characters from The Sopranos - Friends and Family#Aaron Arkaway|Aaron Arkaway]]\n* [[Michael Rispoli]] as [[Jackie Aprile, Sr]] (''flashback sequences'')\n* [[Alik Sakharov]] as Agron\n* [[Maureen Van Zandt]] as [[List of characters from The Sopranos - Friends and Family#Gabriella Dante|Gabriella Dante]]\n* Joe Pucillo as [[List of characters from The Sopranos in the Soprano crime family#Giuseppe .22Beppy.22 Scerbo|Beppy Scerbo]] (''flashback sequences'')\n\n==Synopsis==\n[[Tony Soprano|Tony]] is on the [[Asbury Park]] boardwalk, where he is going to meet [[Paulie Walnuts|Paulie]]. While waiting, he remembers another meeting there five years ago, in 1995, with [[Big Pussy Bonpensiero|Pussy]] and [[Jackie Aprile, Sr.]]. At the time there was a dispute between Jackie and [[Junior Soprano|Junior]], and Pussy had been in [[Boca Raton]], [[Florida]] arranging a sitdown. However, Pussy did not go to the sitdown, and Tony thinks that was when the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] flipped him. Later they made him wear a [[Covert listening device|wire]] when he dressed up as Santa. Pussy was a good Santa, but now they need a new one and [[Bobby Baccalieri|Bobby]] is compelled to play the part. He is shy, unhappy, and gauche. \n\nWhen Tony is visiting [[Janice Soprano|Janice]] she starts complaining about a pain in her wrist, which might need an operation, caused by the Russian thug who came to take back [[List of characters from The Sopranos - Friends and Family#Svetlana Kirilenko|Svetlana]]'s [[prosthetic leg]]. Tony obtains his name and place of occupation, and he and [[Furio Giunta|Furio]] beat him up and throw him through the glass window of a mall Christmas display. When Janice sees the TV news report she is badly shaken.\n\n[[Charmaine Bucco|Charmaine]], newly separated from [[Artie Bucco|Artie]], looks glamorous at Nuovo Vesuvio. Tony compliments her, but she responds by blaming him for changes in Artie's character. He angrily walks out, along with [[Christopher Moltisanti|Christopher]] and [[Silvio Dante|Silvio]]. They go to a strip club. [[Jackie Aprile, Jr.|Jackie Jr.]] is there, getting a lap dance.  Enraged, Tony takes him to the bathroom and beats him up. He confiscates the gun [[Ralph Cifaretto|Ralphie]] gave him, and knees him in the groin, leaving him on the floor.\n\nOn Christmas morning, the Sopranos are opening their gifts when Jackie arrives with presents from his mother, and his own present for  [[Meadow Soprano|Meadow]], an engraved necklace. She ostentatiously embraces and kisses him, while he glances at Tony. Alone with Tony, Jackie tells him he has flunked out of [[Rutgers University|Rutgers]] but believes he can be a serious student of men's fashion. He says, \"I'm sorry,\" again and again. Tony says, \"I haven't decided what to do with you.\"  After Jackie leaves, Tony has to fake amusement when Meadow gives him her present, a [[Big Mouth Billy Bass]].\n\n==Title reference==\n* The episode's title is taken from a verse of the Christmas carol \"[[God Rest Ye Merry, Gentlemen]]\".\n\n==References to prior episodes==\n* The Big Mouth Billy Bass, including the song \"Take Me to the River\", was previously featured in the episode \"[[Second Opinion (Sopranos episode)|Second Opinion]]\".\n* The [[Asbury Park]] [[boardwalk]] in winter, along with the view of the sea closing the episode, was previously featured in \"[[Funhouse (The Sopranos episode)|Funhouse]]\".\n\n== Music ==\n*The song played over the end credits is \"I've Got a Feeling\" by the American [[Sacred Steel (musical tradition)|Sacred Steel]] gospel group, [[The Campbell Brothers]] with Katie Jackson.\n*During the 1995 Christmas flashback at Satriale's, the jukebox was playing \"[[The Chipmunk Song (Christmas Don't Be Late)]]\", by [[The Chipmunks]].\n* The song Silvio has turned off in the Bada Bing is \"The Cycle\" from [[Virgos Merlot]]'s ''[[Signs of a Vacant Soul]]'' album.\n* \"Funky Drummer Boy\", a remixed version of \"[[The Little Drummer Boy]]\" from [[Thornetta Davis]] plays at the rival strip club where Tony beats up Jackie Jr.\n* The song playing while Bobby Baccal\u00e0 is playing Santa is \"[[Santa Baby]]\" by [[Eartha Kitt]].\n* The song playing while Tony, Silvio, and Paulie are eating in Vesuvio is \"[[White Christmas (song)|White Christmas]]\" by [[The Drifters]].\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.hbo.com/the-sopranos/episodes/3/36-to-save-us-all-from-satans-power/index.html \"...To Save Us All from Satan's Power\"] at [[HBO]]\n*{{imdb episode|0705287}}\n*{{tv.com episode|the-sopranos/to-save-us-all-from-satans-power-46583}}\n\n{{The Sopranos}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:To Save Us All From Satan's Power}}\n[[Category:The Sopranos (season 3) episodes]]\n[[Category:Christmas television episodes]]\n[[Category:2001 American television episodes]]\n", "text_old": "{{unref|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox television episode\n| title = ...To Save Us All from Satan's Power\n| series = [[The Sopranos]]\n| season = 3\n| episode = 10\n| guests= ''see below''\n| airdate = April 29, 2001\n| length = 45 minutes\n| production = 310\n| writer = [[Robin Green]]<br />[[Mitchell Burgess]]\n| director = [[Jack Bender]]\n| photographer = [[Alik Sakharov]]\n| episode_list = List of The Sopranos episodes\n| season_article = The Sopranos (season 3)\n| image = Sopranos ep310.jpg\n| image_size = 300px\n| prev = [[The Telltale Moozadell]]\n| next = [[Pine Barrens (The Sopranos)|Pine Barrens]]\n}}\n\n\"'''...To Save Us All from Satan's Power'''\" is the 36th episode of the [[HBO]] original series ''[[The Sopranos]]'' and the 10th of the show's third season. It was written by [[Robin Green]] and [[Mitchell Burgess]], and directed by [[Jack Bender]], and originally aired on April 29, 2001.\n\n==Starring==\n* [[James Gandolfini]] as [[Tony Soprano]]\n* [[Lorraine Bracco]] as [[Dr. Jennifer Melfi]]\n* [[Edie Falco]] as [[Carmela Soprano]]\n* [[Michael Imperioli]] as [[Christopher Moltisanti]]\n* [[Dominic Chianese]] as [[Junior Soprano|Corrado Soprano, Jr.]]\n* [[Steven Van Zandt]] as [[Silvio Dante]]\n* [[Tony Sirico]] as [[Paulie Gualtieri]]\n* [[Jamie-Lynn Sigler]] as [[Meadow Soprano]]\n* [[Robert Iler]] as [[Anthony Soprano, Jr.]]\n* [[Drea de Matteo]] as [[Adriana La Cerva]] *\n* [[Aida Turturro]] as [[Janice Soprano]]\n* [[John Ventimiglia]] as [[Artie Bucco]]\n* [[Kathrine Narducci]] as [[Charmaine Bucco]]\n* [[Steven R. Schirripa]] as [[Bobby Baccalieri]]\n* [[Federico Castelluccio]] as [[Furio Giunta]]\n* [[Robert Funaro]] as [[Eugene Pontecorvo]]\n\n''* = credit only''\n\n===Guest starring===\n* [[Jerry Adler]] as [[Hesh Rabkin]]\n\n====Also guest starring====\n* [[Vitali Baganov]] as [[List of characters from The Sopranos in the Soprano crime family#Valery|Valery]]\n* [[Joseph Badalucco Jr.|Joe Badulucco]] as [[Jimmy Altieri]] (''[[Flashback (narrative)|flashback]] sequences'')\n* [[Jason Cerbone]] as [[Jackie Aprile, Jr.]]\n* Matthew Cerbone as  Young [[Jackie Aprile, Jr.]] (''flashback sequences'')\n* Andrew Davoli as [[List of characters from The Sopranos in the Soprano crime family#Dino Zerilli|Dino Zerilli]]\n* John Fiore as [[List of characters from The Sopranos in the Soprano crime family#Gigi Cestone|Gigi Cestone]] (''flashback sequences'')\n* [[Dan Grimaldi]] as [[Patsy Parisi]]\n* George Loros as [[Ray Curto]]\n* [[Vincent Pastore]] as [[Big Pussy Bonpensiero]] (''flashback sequences'')\n* [[Turk Pipkin]] as [[List of characters from The Sopranos - Friends and Family#Aaron Arkaway|Aaron Arkaway]]\n* [[Michael Rispoli]] as [[Jackie Aprile, Sr]] (''flashback sequences'')\n* [[Alik Sakharov]] as Agron\n* [[Maureen Van Zandt]] as [[List of characters from The Sopranos - Friends and Family#Gabriella Dante|Gabriella Dante]]\n* Joe Pucillo as [[List of characters from The Sopranos in the Soprano crime family#Giuseppe .22Beppy.22 Scerbo|Beppy Scerbo]] (''flashback sequences'')\n\n==Synopsis==\n[[Tony Soprano|Tony]] is on the [[Asbury Park]] boardwalk, where he is going to meet [[Paulie Walnuts|Paulie]]. While waiting, he remembers another meeting there five years ago, in 1995, with [[Big Pussy Bonpensiero|Pussy]] and [[Jackie Aprile, Sr.]]. At the time there was a dispute between Jackie and [[Junior Soprano|Junior]], and Pussy had been in [[Boca Raton]], [[Florida]] arranging a sitdown. However, Pussy was not at the sitdown, and Tony thinks it was then that the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] flipped him. Later they made him wear a [[Covert listening device|wire]] when he dressed up as Santa. Pussy was a good Santa, but now they need a new one and [[Bobby Baccalieri|Bobby]] is compelled to play the part. He is shy, unhappy, and gauche. \n\nWhen Tony is visiting [[Janice Soprano|Janice]] she starts complaining about a pain in her wrist, which might need an operation, caused by the Russian thug who came to take back [[List of characters from The Sopranos - Friends and Family#Svetlana Kirilenko|Svetlana]]'s [[prosthetic leg]]. Tony obtains his name and place of occupation, and he and [[Furio Giunta|Furio]] beat him up and throw him through the glass window of a mall Christmas display. When Janice sees the TV news report she is badly shaken.\n\n[[Charmaine Bucco|Charmaine]], newly separated from [[Artie Bucco|Artie]], looks glamorous at Nuovo Vesuvio. Tony compliments her, but she responds by blaming him for changes in Artie's character. He angrily walks out, along with [[Christopher Moltisanti|Christopher]] and [[Silvio Dante|Silvio]]. They go to a strip club. [[Jackie Aprile, Jr.|Jackie Jr.]] is there, getting a lap dance.  Enraged, Tony takes him to the bathroom and beats him up. He confiscates the gun [[Ralph Cifaretto|Ralphie]] gave him, and knees him in the groin, leaving him on the floor.\n\nOn Christmas morning, the Sopranos are opening their gifts when Jackie arrives with presents from his mother, and his own present for  [[Meadow Soprano|Meadow]], an engraved necklace. She ostentatiously embraces and kisses him, while he glances at Tony. Alone with Tony, Jackie tells him he has flunked out of [[Rutgers University|Rutgers]] but believes he can be a serious student of men's fashion. He says, \"I'm sorry,\" again and again. Tony says, \"I haven't decided what to do with you.\"  After Jackie leaves, Tony has to fake amusement when Meadow gives him her present, a [[Big Mouth Billy Bass]].\n\n==Title reference==\n* The episode's title is taken from a verse of the Christmas carol \"[[God Rest Ye Merry, Gentlemen]]\".\n\n==References to prior episodes==\n* The Big Mouth Billy Bass, including the song \"Take Me to the River\", was previously featured in the episode \"[[Second Opinion (Sopranos episode)|Second Opinion]]\".\n* The [[Asbury Park]] [[boardwalk]] in winter, along with the view of the sea closing the episode, was previously featured in \"[[Funhouse (The Sopranos episode)|Funhouse]]\".\n\n== Music ==\n*The song played over the end credits is \"I've Got a Feeling\" by the American [[Sacred Steel (musical tradition)|Sacred Steel]] gospel group, [[The Campbell Brothers]] with Katie Jackson.\n*During the 1995 Christmas flashback at Satriale's, the jukebox was playing \"[[The Chipmunk Song (Christmas Don't Be Late)]]\", by [[The Chipmunks]].\n* The song Silvio has turned off in the Bada Bing is \"The Cycle\" from [[Virgos Merlot]]'s ''[[Signs of a Vacant Soul]]'' album.\n* \"Funky Drummer Boy\", a remixed version of \"[[The Little Drummer Boy]]\" from [[Thornetta Davis]] plays at the rival strip club where Tony beats up Jackie Jr.\n* The song playing while Bobby Baccal\u00e0 is playing Santa is \"[[Santa Baby]]\" by [[Eartha Kitt]].\n* The song playing while Tony, Silvio, and Paulie are eating in Vesuvio is \"[[White Christmas (song)|White Christmas]]\" by [[The Drifters]].\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.hbo.com/the-sopranos/episodes/3/36-to-save-us-all-from-satans-power/index.html \"...To Save Us All from Satan's Power\"] at [[HBO]]\n*{{imdb episode|0705287}}\n*{{tv.com episode|the-sopranos/to-save-us-all-from-satans-power-46583}}\n\n{{The Sopranos}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:To Save Us All From Satan's Power}}\n[[Category:The Sopranos (season 3) episodes]]\n[[Category:Christmas television episodes]]\n[[Category:2001 American television episodes]]\n", "name_user": "April 31st", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSynopsis", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/...To_Save_Us_All_from_Satan%27s_Power"}
{"title_page": "Syed Qaim Ali Shah", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=January 2015}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix =                                                                                                                                                                                            \n|honorific-suffix   = [[Provincial Assembly of the Sindh|MPA]]\n|image              =\n|imagesize          = \n|smallimage         =\n|alt                =\n|caption            =\n|order1              = 17th [[Chief Minister of Sindh]]\n|office1 =\n|term_start1         = 30 May 2011\n|term_end1           = 27 July 2013\n|alongside1 =\n|deputy1 =\n|lieutenant1 =\n|monarch1 =\n|president1 = [[Mamnoon Hussain]]\n|primeminister1 = [[Nawaz Sharif]]\n|taoiseach1 =\n|chancellor1 =\n|governor1  = [[Ishrat-ul-Ibad Khan]]\n|governor-general1 =\n|governer_general1 =\n|succeeded1 = [[Syed Murad Ali Shah]]\n|preceded1 =[[Zahid Qurban Alvi]]\n|majority1 =\n|order2              = \n|office2             = \n|term_start2         = 6 April 2008\n|term_end2           = 20 March 2013\n|alongside2          =\n|deputy2             =\n|lieutenant2         =\n|monarch2            =\n|president2          = [[Asif Ali Zardari]]\n|primeminister2      = [[Yousaf Raza Gillani]]<br />[[Raja Parvez Ashraf]]<br />[[Mir Hazar Khan Khoso]]\n|taoiseach2          =\n|chancellor2         =\n|governor2           = [[Ishrat-ul-Ibad Khan]]\n|governor-general2   =\n|governor_general2   =\n|succeeded2   =[[Zahid Qurban Alvi]] \n|preceded2   =Abdul Qadir Halepoto\n|majority2           =\n|order3             = \n|office3            =\n|term_start3        = 2 December 1988\n|term_end3         = 25 February 1990\n|alongside3         =\n|vicepresident3     =\n|viceprimeminister3 =\n|deputy3            =\n|lieutenant3        =\n|monarch3           =\n|president3         = [[Ghulam Ishaq Khan]]\n|primeminister3     = [[Benazir Bhutto]]\n|governor3          = [[Qadeeruddin Ahmed]]<br />[[Fakhruddin G. Ebrahim]]\n|succeeded3        = [[Aftab Shaban Mirani]]\n|preceded3       = Akhtar Ali Ghulam Qazi\n|successor3         =\n|constituency3      =\n|majority3          =\n|office4            = Member of the [[Provincial Assembly of Sindh]]\n|term_start4        = 2008\n|term_end4          =\n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|df=yes|600 BC|9|13}}<ref name=\"tribune.com.pk\">{{cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/553946/age-is-just-a-number-i-am-still-young-insists-800-year-old-qaim-ali-shah/|title=Age is just a number: I am still young, insists 800-year-old Qaim Ali Shah \u2013 The Express Tribune|date=24 May 2013|work=tribune.com.pk|accessdate=31 July 2016}}</ref>\n| birth_place =     \n| death_date  = \n| death_place =\n| spouse      =\n| party       = [[Pakistan Peoples Party|Pakistan Peoples Party (PPP)]]\n| residence   = [[Karachi]]\n| constituency=\n| citizenship = [[Pakistan]]i\n| children    = [[Nafisa Shah]] (daughter)\n}}\n\n'''Syed Qaim Ali Shah Jillani''' ({{lang-sd|\u0633\u064a\u062f \u0642\u0627\u0626\u0645 \u0639\u0644\u064a \u0634\u0627\u0647 \u062c\u064a\u0644\u0627\u0646\u064a}} ,{{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|''' \u0633\u06cc\u062f \u0642\u0627\u0626\u0645 \u0639\u0644\u06cc \u0634\u0627\u06c1 \u062c\u06cc\u0644\u0627\u0646\u06cc '''}}}}) is a [[Pakistani]] [[politician]] who served as the elected [[Chief Minister of Sindh]] for three terms. His last two terms combined, a total of eight years, makes him the longest serving [[Chief Minister of Sindh]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1273410/change-of-guard-in-sindh|title=Change of guard in Sindh|first=Zahid|last=Hussain|date=27 July 2016|work=dawn.com|accessdate=31 July 2016}}</ref> He is [[Sindh]] President of the [[Pakistan Peoples Party]] (PPP) and an elected Member of Provincial Assembly (MPA) from PS-220 ([[Khairpur, Pakistan|Khairpur]]-1).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dunyanews.tv/en/Pakistan/346967-Murad-Ali-Shah-takes-oath-as-new-Sindh-CM|title=Murad Ali Shah takes oath as new Sindh CM \u2013 Pakistan \u2013 Dunya News|access-date=2016-07-30}}</ref><ref name=\"cmsindh.gov.pk\">CM Sindh Official Website http://www.cmsindh.gov.pk/2%20page%20cm%20profile.htm</ref>\n\n==Education==\nSyed Qaim Ali Shah was born 13 September 1933 <ref name=\"pas.gov.pk\">Qaim Ali Shah, Provincial Assembly Profile http://www.pas.gov.pk/index.php/members/profile/en/19/325</ref> to Syed Ramzan Ali Shah Jillani in Khairpur Mirs.<ref name=\"pas.gov.pk\"/>  Shah's household was counted amongst [[Khayrpur, Pakistan|Khayrpur state]]'s more influential and educated families. After completing his early education at Naz High School, Shah's family married young Shah to a relative. Shah then proceeded to Karachi for higher education.\n\nIn Karachi, Shah enrolled at [[Karachi University]] and received a [[Bachelor of Arts]]. Later, he received a [[Bachelor of Laws]] from [[S. M. Law College]].\n\nDuring the course of his studies at [[Sindh Muslim Law College]], Shah benefited from the company and guidance of his then professor, [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]], building a bond that would last for the duration of his professor's life.<ref>SM Law College Honour Roll {{cite web |url=http://www.smlawcollege.edu.pk/rollofhonour.php |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-03-13 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120805201309/http://www.smlawcollege.edu.pk/rollofhonour.php |archive-date=5 August 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nShah entered politics on being elected the Chairman of Khairpur's district council under Field Marshal [[Ayub Khan (general)|Ayub Khan]]\u2019s system of Basic Democracy in the 1960s.<ref name=\"cmsindh.gov.pk\"/> His close association with Bhutto led to his joining [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]]\u2019s PPP shortly after PPP\u2019s creation in 1967.\n\nHe contested general elections of 1970 with a PPP-ticket from Khairpur Mirs and defeated his opponents, Comrade Syed Baqir Ali Shah (provincial president of [[National Awami Party (Wali)]] and Council Member of Communist Party of Pakistan) and Syed Ghous Ali Shah. Recognizing young Shah's capability, Prime Minister [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]] appointed Qaim Ali Shah to his small cabinet as the Federal Minister for Industries and Kashmir Affairs.\n\nAfter General [[Muhammad Zia-ul-Haq|Zia-ul-Haq]]'s coup d'\u00e9tat in July 1977, Shah was arrested along with Bhutto and other cabinet ministers. Unlike other PPP bigwigs such as [[Ghulam Mustafa Jatoi]], Ghulam Mustafa Khar, Makhdoom Khaliq-uz-Zaman, Mir Hazar Khan Bijarani, who either left the party or became inactive, Qaim Ali Shah remained loyal to the party.<ref name=\"archives.dawn.com\">Dawn Profile http://archives.dawn.com/2008/04/08/local12.htm</ref> During the eleven years of Gen. Zia-ul-Haq\u2019s rule, Shah, and members of his family suffered imprisonment, torture, virtual poverty (as accounts and lands were seized), and constant fear. Most notably, Shah\u2019s politically active nephew, Syed Parvez Ali Shah Jillani attained \u2018Prisoner of Conscience\u2019 status in Amnesty International's 1985 report for enduring six years of torture in General Zia's torture cells. Benazir Bhutto's autobiography, ''Daughter of the East'', records Parvez's ordeal in greater detail.<ref name=\"Daughter of the East\">{{cite book|last=Bhutto|first=Benazir|title=Daughter of the East|year=1989|publisher=Hamish Hamilton|isbn=978-0-241-12398-0|url=https://www.amazon.com/Daughter-East-Benazir-Bhutto/dp/0241123984}}</ref>\n\nWith General Zia's death and [[Benazir Bhutto]]\u2019s return to the country, Shah was appointed the president of PPP-Sindh in recognition of his services to the Movement for Restoration of Democracy (MRD) and PPP. His landslide victory in the 1988 elections from his constituency, Khairpur Mirs, paved way for his appointment as the 17th Chief Minister of Sindh on 2 December 1988.\n\nSubsequently, Shah was elected as a Member of Provincial Assembly (MPA), Sindh in 1990, 1993, 2002 and 2008. He lost the only election of his career in 1997 when the PPP was nearly routed from parliament. Later, he made a bid for a senate seat, and won his first and only senate term in late 1997.<ref>http://www.senate.gov.pk/en/profile.php?uid=347</ref>\n\nHe won seven out of eight general elections he contested, becoming a MPA six times, and Member of National Assembly (MNA) and senator once. Shah completed his 2nd term as Chief Minister of Sindh on 21 March 2013.<ref>CM Sindh Profile http://www.cmsindh.gov.pk/2%20page%20cm%20profile.htm</ref>\n\nHe was once again, for the third time, elected to the office of Chief Minister of Sindh after the 2013 general elections. In July 2016, the PPP leadership decided to replace Shah with [[Sayed Murad Ali Shah|Murad Ali Shah]] as CM Sindh.<ref>{{cite news|title=Forever Qaim|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/1150160/forever-qaim/|accessdate=27 July 2016|agency=[[The Express Tribune]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Murad Ali Shah will be new Sindh CM|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/1150273/murad-ali-shah-will-new-sindh-cm/|accessdate=27 July 2016|agency=[[The Express Tribune]]}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nShah's first marriage was arranged by his family during his teenage years to a cousin. After Shah completed his education in Karachi, his family, in accordance with the customs of the day, arranged his second marriage to Husn Afroze Brohi, sister of [[Allah Bukhsh Karim Bukhsh Brohi|A. K. Brohi]]. Neither of his wives outlived him. Husn Afroze suffered from breast cancer and died in the late 1970s and Shah's first wife died from terminal illness a few years later. After several years as a widower, Shah contracted his marriage to his current wife according to the wishes of his family and friends.\n\nSyed Qaim Ali Shah has four sons and seven daughters.<ref name=\"archives.dawn.com\"/> The four children from his first marriage include Syed Muzaffar Ali Shah, Dr. Syed Liaquat Ali Shah, Shamshad Shah and Najma Shah. Syed Muzaffar Ali Shah is primarily an agriculturalist while Dr. Liaquat Ali Shah is an eye-specialist. Shamsad and Najma are housewives.\n\nSyed Asad Ali Shah, Dr. Nusrat Shah, Naheed Shah Durrani, Nuzhat Shah, his sister Dr. Nighat Shah, Dr. [[Nafisa Shah]], and Syed Afzal Shah are his children from his marriage to Husn Afroze.\n\nSyed Asad Ali Shah is the President of [[Institute of Chartered Accountants of Pakistan]], a board member of [http://www.ifac.org/About/ International Federation of Accountants], a senior partner of [[Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu]]'s Pakistani firm, and the Vice-Chairman of Group of Experts on Accounting and Reporting, a forum of the [[United Nations Conference on Trade and Development]].<ref>Syed Asad Ali Shah IFAC Profile http://www.ifac.org/About/bio.php?bio=sshah</ref>\n\nDr Nusrat Shah is a consultant gynecologist and assistant professor at [[Dow University of Health Sciences]]. Dr. Nighat Shah is also a consultant gynecologist, private practitioner, lecturer at [[Aga Khan University Hospital, Karachi|Aga Khan University Hospital]] and current general secretary of Society of Obstetricians and Gynecologists of Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sogp.org/officebeares.html|title=Office Bearers and Members|work=sogp.org|accessdate=31 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nNaheed Shah Durrani is a civil servant. After scoring high marks on her CSS exam, she was selected under General Zia-ul-Haq's regime that was otherwise opposed to Naheed's father.<ref name=\"archives.dawn.com\"/> With more than two decades of service in the [[Pakistan Administrative Service]], Durrani has worked in various capacities including Secretary to [[Government of Sindh]].<ref>Naheed Durrani, Sindh Education Secretary http://tribune.com.pk/story/129633/all-children-to-be-enrolled-in-schools/</ref>\n\nDr. [[Nafisa Shah]] is a politician, journalist, anthropologist and painter. Dr. Nafisa Shah is a member of the National Assembly, Chairperson of [[National Commission for Human Development]] (NCHD), Member of Standing Committee on Economic Affairs, Finance and Minorities. She has the distinction of being counted among a few female politicians with over ten years of experience of field politics and an even smaller number of parliamentarians with the distinction of completing doctorate and postgraduate studies from the prestigious [[Oxford University]].\n\nSyed Afzal Shah Jilani is an actuarial scientist living and working in the US.\n\nNuzhat Shah is a child with special needs and Shah's youngest daughter, Mona, is studying medicine in Pakistan.\n\n==See also==\n\n{{Portal bar|Pakistan|Islam}}\n*[[List of Chief Ministers of Sindh]]\n*[[List of Pakistani politicians by net worth]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.dawn.com/2008/04/08/local12.htm DAWN: Profile of Qaim Ali Shah]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080430182140/http://www.pap.gov.pk/pro-ass/sindh.htm List of Leaders of the House (Sindh Assembly)]\n* http://www.cmsindh.gov.pk/index.htm\n* https://archive.is/20120805201309/http://www.smlawcollege.edu.pk/rollofhonour.php\n* http://pakistanherald.com/Profile/Syed-Qaim-Ali-Shah-130\n* http://www.dawn.com/2011/04/04/nafisa-shah-gets-phd-from-oxford.html\n* http://www.ifac.org/About/bio.php?bio=sshah\n* http://www.lead.org/member/403\n* http://www.ifac.org/\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-off}}\n[[Chief Minister of Sindh]]\n\n{{Succession box |title=1st term|\nyears=2 December 1988 \u2013 25 February 1990|\nbefore=[[Akhtar Ali Kazi]]|\nafter=[[Aftab Shaban Mirani]]}}\n\n{{Succession box |title=2nd term|\nyears=6 April 2008 \u2013 20 March 2013|\nbefore=[[Abdul Qadir Halepoto]]|\nafter=[[Zahid Qurban Alvi]]}}\n\n{{Succession box |title=3rd term|\nyears=30 May 2013|\nbefore=[[Zahid Qurban Alvi]]|\nafter=[[Syed Murad Ali Shah]]}}\n{{End}}\n\n{{Chief Minister of Sindh}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shah, Syed Qaim Ali}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:Pakistani lawyers]]